ories of analysis in direct reference to infrastructure, providing unique insights into the political and cultural processes that took place across Europe after the Cold War. More specifically, it sheds light on political and economic relationships in the Balkans during the socialist post-Cold War period, focusing especially on Albania, one of the most under-researched countries in the region.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAnthropologyxBalkan PeninsulaxBalkan Peninsula. 0aAnthropologyzBalkan Peninsula. 0aEthnologyxBalkan Peninsula. 0aEthnologyzBalkan Peninsula. 0aInfrastructure (Economics)xSocial aspectszBalkan Peninsula. 0aRoadsxSocial aspectsxBalkan Peninsula. 0aRoadsxSocial aspectszBalkan Peninsula. 0aTransportation geographyzBalkan Peninsula. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aAlbania.  aBalkans.  aBorders.  aCritical Studies.  aGreece.  aHouse.  aInfrastructures.  aMigration.  aMobility.  aUrban Development.1 aDalakoglou, Dimitris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packagez978311128281740uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152610935440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526109354423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526109354/original  a978-3-11-128281-7  Manchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packageb2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles